Cancer is a group of diseases involving uncontrolled cell growth and the ability of these cells to invade other tissues.  It can affect almost any part of the body and is a leading cause of death worldwide.  The occurrence of cancer increases with age, with most cases diagnosed in people over 65.  Common cancers include skin, lung, colon, breast (in women), and prostate (in men).  About 1.2 million Americans are diagnosed annually, and over 500,000 die from cancer each year in the US.  One out of every four deaths in the United States is from cancer.

The provided text describes two types of diabetes:

**Diabetes Insipidus:** This is a condition where the body can't regulate fluid balance properly, leading to excessive thirst and urination.  It's treated with adequate water intake and sometimes medication.  The prognosis is generally good with proper management.

**Diabetes Mellitus:** This is a chronic disease where the body doesn't produce enough insulin or can't use insulin effectively, resulting in high blood sugar.  There are different types, and symptoms can include frequent urination, thirst, hunger, weight loss, slow wound healing, and vision problems. Treatment involves diet changes, medication, and sometimes insulin injections.  It can lead to serious complications like kidney failure, heart disease, stroke, and blindness.

Kidney failure is triggered by disease or a hereditary disorder affecting the kidneys.  Common causes include diabetes, glomerulonephritis, hypertension, and polycystic kidney disease.  Other potential causes include kidney cancer, kidney stones, pyelonephritis, reflux nephropathy, systemic lupus erythematosus, amyloidosis, sickle cell anemia, Alport syndrome, and oxalosis.
